<h2 id="rnngru-architecture">RNN(GRU) Architecture</h2>

<p><img src="https://stanford.edu/~shervine/teaching/cs-230/illustrations/architecture-rnn-ltr.png?9ea4417fc145b9346a3e288801dbdfdc" alt="img" /></p>

<p>In our reseach project, \(x^{&lt;t&gt;}\) stands for the i-th bit in block. For each bit at position \(t\) , the activation</p>

<p>\(a^{&lt;t&gt;}\) updated as \(a^{\langle t\rangle}=g_1\left(W_{a a} a^{&lt;t-1\rangle}+W_{a x} x^{&lt;t\rangle}+b_a\right)\) and  \(y^{&lt;t&gt;}\) updated as \(y^{&lt;t&gt;}=g_2\left(W_{y a} a^{&lt;t&gt;}+b_y\right)\) , where \(W_{a x}, W_{a a}, W_{y a}, b_a, b_y\) are coefficients shared temporally.</p>

<h3 id="loss-funciton-of-rnn">Loss funciton of RNN</h3>

\[\mathcal{L}(\widehat{y}, y)=\sum_{t=1}^{T_y} \mathcal{L}\left(\widehat{y}^{&lt;t&gt;}, y^{&lt;t&gt;}\right)\]

<h3 id="backpropagation-through-time">Backpropagation through time</h3>

\[\frac{\partial \mathcal{L}^{(T)}}{\partial W}=\left.\sum_{t=1}^T \frac{\partial \mathcal{L}^{(T)}}{\partial W}\right|_{(t)}\]

<p>Backpropagation is done at each point in time. At timestep $T$, the derivative of the loss $\mathcal{L}$ with respect to weight matrix $W$ is expressed as above.</p>

